<div class="content-wrap">
  <main class="main-content">

    <section class="section" id="overview">
      <h2>CR-1 Timeline Overview (2026)</h2>
      <p>The CR-1 spousal immigrant visa follows a four-stage pipeline: USCIS adjudicates the I-130 petition, then the National Visa Center (NVC) collects fees and documents, then a U.S. embassy conducts the interview and issues the visa, and finally your spouse enters the U.S. and receives their green card. Each stage has its own queue.</p>
      <p>In 2026, the dominant bottleneck is <strong>USCIS I-130 adjudication</strong>, which accounts for roughly 60–70% of total wait time. NVC processing is the second-longest stage — unlike the K-1, the CR-1 requires full document submission through NVC before the interview can be scheduled. Embassy wait times vary significantly by country.</p>
      <p>The key advantage of the CR-1 over the K-1: your spouse enters the U.S. as a <strong>lawful permanent resident</strong> (green card holder) on day one, skipping the separate Adjustment of Status process. For the total path to a green card, the CR-1 is often comparable or faster than the K-1 + AOS route.</p>
      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>Always verify at the official source:</strong> Processing times change monthly. Check current I-130 times at <strong>egov.uscis.gov/processing-times</strong> and NVC case status at <strong>ceac.state.gov</strong>. The times on this page reflect April 2026 data.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="stage1">
      <h2>Stage 1 — USCIS I-130 Processing (12–18 months)</h2>

      <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-head">
          <div class="stage-num">1</div>
          <div class="stage-head-info">
            <div class="stage-head-title">USCIS Adjudication of Form I-130</div>
            <div class="stage-head-sub">From filing to approval notice</div>
          </div>
          <span class="stage-time-badge">12–18 months</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-body">
          <p>After filing Form I-130 (Petition for Alien Relative), USCIS issues a receipt notice (Form I-797C) within 2–6 weeks. The case then enters the adjudication queue. USCIS reviews your evidence, verifies the bona fide marriage, and either approves, issues an RFE (Request for Evidence), or denies.</p>
          <p>The I-130 goes through several internal steps:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Receipt notice</strong> — issued within 2–6 weeks of filing; contains your case number</li>
            <li><strong>Biometrics appointment</strong> — if required (typically for certain filing scenarios; not always required for immediate relative petitions)</li>
            <li><strong>Adjudication</strong> — an officer reviews the file; may issue an RFE</li>
            <li><strong>Approval notice</strong> — Form I-797 approval; case transfers to NVC</li>
          </ul>
          <p>For spouses of U.S. citizens (IR-1/CR-1 category), there is no visa number backlog — you are an Immediate Relative, and visas are always available. The only wait is USCIS adjudication and subsequent processing.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>USCIS processing times by filing location (April 2026)</h3>
      <p>Where you mail your I-130 (Chicago Lockbox vs. Dallas Lockbox) determines which service center handles your case. USCIS assigns cases internally based on workload.</p>
      <table class="sc-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Service Center / Office</th><th>Current Processing Time</th><th>Status</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>California Service Center (CSC)</td>
            <td class="slow">14–18 months</td>
            <td>Slower than average</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Vermont Service Center (VSC)</td>
            <td class="mid">12–16 months</td>
            <td>Near average</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Texas Service Center (TSC)</td>
            <td class="mid">13–17 months</td>
            <td>Near average</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>National Benefits Center (NBC)</td>
            <td class="fast">10–14 months</td>
            <td>Faster than average</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Chicago Lockbox → routed to service center</td>
            <td class="mid">12–18 months</td>
            <td>Depends on assignment</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Dallas Lockbox → routed to service center</td>
            <td class="mid">12–18 months</td>
            <td>Depends on assignment</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p style="font-size:0.8rem; color: var(--color-muted);">* Times are approximate and change monthly. Verify at egov.uscis.gov/processing-times — select "I-130, Petition for Alien Relative" and "Immediate Relative."</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <p><strong>Outside the published processing time?</strong> If your I-130 has been pending longer than USCIS's posted time for your service center, submit a case inquiry (service request) at my.uscis.gov. For cases significantly outside normal time, contact your U.S. Congressional representative — their immigration caseworkers can submit a formal inquiry that often moves stuck cases.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="stage2">
      <h2>Stage 2 — NVC Processing (3–6 months)</h2>

      <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-head">
          <div class="stage-num">2</div>
          <div class="stage-head-info">
            <div class="stage-head-title">National Visa Center — Fees, Documents &amp; Interview Scheduling</div>
            <div class="stage-head-sub">From USCIS approval to embassy interview scheduled</div>
          </div>
          <span class="stage-time-badge">3–6 months</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-body">
          <p>After USCIS approves the I-130, the case transfers to the NVC in Portsmouth, NH. Unlike the K-1 process, the CR-1 NVC stage is substantive — you must pay fees and submit a complete document package before NVC will schedule your spouse's interview.</p>
          <p>NVC communicates through the CEAC portal at ceac.state.gov. Both the petitioner (U.S. citizen) and the beneficiary (the spouse abroad) have tasks to complete.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>NVC timeline table</h3>
      <table class="nvc-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>NVC Step</th><th>What Happens</th><th>Typical Wait</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Case number assigned</strong></td>
            <td>NVC assigns a case number and invoice ID; sends welcome email to petitioner</td>
            <td>2–6 weeks after USCIS approval</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Fee payment</strong></td>
            <td>Pay the IV fee ($325) and Affidavit of Support fee ($120) through CEAC</td>
            <td>1–4 weeks after welcome email</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Document submission</strong></td>
            <td>Upload I-864 (Affidavit of Support), DS-260 (immigrant visa application), civil documents (birth cert, marriage cert, police certs, etc.)</td>
            <td>2–6 weeks to compile and upload</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>NVC review</strong></td>
            <td>NVC officer reviews entire package for completeness and correctness; may request additional documents (a "checklist")</td>
            <td>4–12 weeks</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Case complete</strong></td>
            <td>NVC marks the case "documentarily qualified" and transfers to the embassy for interview scheduling</td>
            <td>After review is passed</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Interview scheduled</strong></td>
            <td>Embassy contacts beneficiary with interview date; medical exam should be completed before interview</td>
            <td>2–6 weeks after case complete</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="tip">
        <p><strong>Submit everything at once.</strong> NVC reviews your package as a whole. If anything is missing, they send a "checklist" and your case goes back to the review queue — adding weeks or months. Prepare all documents before submitting anything.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="stage3">
      <h2>Stage 3 — Embassy / Consulate (2–4 months)</h2>

      <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-head">
          <div class="stage-num">3</div>
          <div class="stage-head-info">
            <div class="stage-head-title">Embassy Interview, Medical Exam &amp; Visa Issuance</div>
            <div class="stage-head-sub">From NVC case complete to visa in hand</div>
          </div>
          <span class="stage-time-badge">2–4 months</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-body">
          <p>Once the embassy receives the case from NVC, they schedule the immigrant visa interview. The interview itself is typically 10–30 minutes. If approved, the visa is stamped into the passport and returned within 1–5 business days via courier.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Medical exam</strong> — must be completed with a USCIS-designated physician (panel physician) before the interview; results are typically valid for 2 years</li>
            <li><strong>Interview scheduling</strong> — wait varies by country and embassy workload</li>
            <li><strong>Interview</strong> — officer verifies the bona fide marriage and admissibility</li>
            <li><strong>Visa issuance</strong> — CR-1 visa stamped; typically valid for 6 months for travel to the U.S.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Top embassy wait times by country (April 2026)</h3>
      <table class="country-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Country / Post</th><th>Avg. Interview Wait</th><th>CR-1 Volume</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇲🇽</span>Mexico (Ciudad Juárez)</td><td>3–5 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-high">Very High</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇵🇭</span>Philippines (Manila)</td><td>3–5 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-high">Very High</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇮🇳</span>India (Mumbai, Chennai, Delhi)</td><td>3–5 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-high">Very High</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇧🇷</span>Brazil (São Paulo)</td><td>2–4 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-high">High</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇨🇳</span>China (Guangzhou)</td><td>3–5 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-high">High</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇬🇧</span>United Kingdom (London)</td><td>1–2 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-mid">Medium</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇦🇺</span>Australia (Sydney)</td><td>1–2 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-low">Lower</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇩🇪</span>Germany (Frankfurt)</td><td>1–2 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-low">Lower</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇨🇦</span>Canada (Ottawa, Toronto)</td><td>1–2 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-low">Lower</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="country-flag">🇰🇷</span>South Korea (Seoul)</td><td>1–2 months</td><td><span class="vol-badge vol-low">Lower</span></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p style="font-size:0.8rem; color: var(--color-muted);">* Embassy interview wait times fluctuate. Check Visa Appointment Wait Times at travel.state.gov for the most current data for your specific post.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="stage4">
      <h2>Stage 4 — Entry &amp; Green Card (1–2 months)</h2>

      <div class="stage-card">
        <div class="stage-head">
          <div class="stage-num">4</div>
          <div class="stage-head-info">
            <div class="stage-head-title">U.S. Entry, CBP Inspection &amp; Green Card by Mail</div>
            <div class="stage-head-sub">From visa in hand to green card delivered</div>
          </div>
          <span class="stage-time-badge">1–2 months</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-body">
          <p>Your spouse enters the U.S. on the CR-1 immigrant visa. At the port of entry, a CBP officer inspects the sealed visa packet and admits your spouse as a lawful permanent resident (LPR). The CR-1 visa itself is not the green card — the physical green card (Form I-551) is mailed separately.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>CBP inspection</strong> — at the port of entry; typically 15–60 minutes; the sealed visa packet from the embassy is opened and reviewed</li>
            <li><strong>I-551 stamp</strong> — CBP may stamp the passport as temporary evidence of LPR status while the card is produced</li>
            <li><strong>Green card by mail</strong> — USCIS produces and mails the physical I-551 green card within 4–8 weeks; it will go to the U.S. address on file</li>
            <li><strong>CR-1 vs. IR-1</strong> — if married less than 2 years at time of entry, the card is a 2-year conditional green card (CR-1); married 2+ years, it's a 10-year permanent card (IR-1). CR-1 holders must file Form I-751 to remove conditions before the 2-year card expires.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="uscis-table">
      <h2>Full CR-1 Timeline Summary Table</h2>
      <table class="sc-table">
