    <section class="section" id="cr1-vs-k1">
      <h2>CR-1 vs. K-1 Processing Time Comparison</h2>
      <p>The CR-1 takes longer to get your spouse into the U.S., but the K-1 requires an additional 12–24 month Adjustment of Status process after arrival. For the total path to a green card, the CR-1 is often comparable or faster overall.</p>

      <div class="compare-grid">
        <div class="compare-card cr1">
          <div class="compare-card-head">CR-1 Spousal Visa</div>
          <div class="time">~18–24 months to entry</div>
          <ul>
            <li class="pro">Spouse enters as lawful permanent resident (green card on day 1)</li>
            <li class="pro">No Adjustment of Status process after arrival (saves 12–24 months + ~$1,440)</li>
            <li class="pro">No 90-day marriage deadline after entry</li>
            <li class="pro">Work authorization and travel rights immediately upon entry</li>
            <li class="con">Longer wait before spouse can enter the U.S.</li>
            <li class="con">NVC document stage adds 3–6 months vs. K-1's 3–6 weeks at NVC</li>
            <li class="con">CR-1 (married &lt; 2 years) requires I-751 to remove conditions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-card k1">
          <div class="compare-card-head">K-1 Fiancé Visa</div>
          <div class="time">~12–18 months to entry</div>
          <ul>
            <li class="pro">Faster to get partner physically in the U.S.</li>
            <li class="pro">NVC stage is much shorter (3–6 weeks vs. 3–6 months)</li>
            <li class="pro">Allows time to plan the wedding after arrival</li>
            <li class="con">Enters as a nonimmigrant — must apply for green card separately (AOS)</li>
            <li class="con">AOS adds 12–24 months and ~$1,440 in fees after arrival</li>
            <li class="con">Must marry within 90 days of entry or depart</li>
            <li class="con">Work authorization may take 3–5 months to arrive after filing AOS</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> If getting your spouse to the U.S. faster is the top priority and you are already married, the CR-1 is the right path — they arrive as a green card holder. If you are not yet married and need to be together sooner, the K-1 gets them here faster but requires an additional AOS process. See the <SmartLink href="/k1-vs-cr1">K-1 vs. CR-1 full comparison</SmartLink> for more detail.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="check-status">
      <h2>How to Check Your CR-1 Case Status</h2>
      <ul class="check-steps">
        <li class="check-step">
          <div class="check-step-num">1</div>
          <div class="check-step-body">
            <h4>USCIS stage — my.uscis.gov</h4>
            <p>Use your I-130 receipt number (starts with EAC, WAC, LIN, MSC, or IOE) to check your case status at <a href="https://my.uscis.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">my.uscis.gov</a>. Statuses include "Case Received," "Case Is Being Actively Reviewed," "Request for Evidence Sent," and "Case Was Approved." Sign up for email and SMS notifications so you hear instantly when status changes.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="check-step">
          <div class="check-step-num">2</div>
          <div class="check-step-body">
            <h4>NVC stage — ceac.state.gov</h4>
            <p>Once NVC has your case, log in to <a href="https://ceac.state.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ceac.state.gov</a> using your NVC case number and beneficiary's date of birth. You can track fee payment status, document submission status, review status, and whether the case is marked "Documentarily Qualified" (ready for interview scheduling).</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="check-step">
          <div class="check-step-num">3</div>
          <div class="check-step-body">
            <h4>Embassy stage — contact the post directly</h4>
            <p>After NVC marks the case complete and transfers it to the embassy, contact that embassy directly for interview scheduling information. Most U.S. embassies have dedicated immigrant visa inquiry email addresses and/or online inquiry systems listed on their official website at <a href="https://www.usembassy.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">usembassy.gov</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="check-step">
          <div class="check-step-num">4</div>
          <div class="check-step-body">
            <h4>If stuck — Congressional inquiry</h4>
            <p>Contact your U.S. Representative or Senator's office (use the petitioner's Congressional district). Most have dedicated immigration caseworkers who can submit a formal congressional inquiry to USCIS or the State Department. This is free, legal, and often effective for cases that are significantly outside normal processing times.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="delays">
      <h2>What Causes CR-1 Delays?</h2>
      <div class="factors-grid">
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">📋</div>
          <h4>Request for Evidence (RFE)</h4>
          <p>USCIS issues an RFE when the initial I-130 filing lacks sufficient evidence of a bona fide marriage. Responding takes time and the case clock pauses — an RFE can add 3–6 months.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">📁</div>
          <h4>Missing or incomplete NVC documents</h4>
          <p>NVC sends a "checklist" if your package is incomplete. This returns the case to the review queue, often adding 4–12 weeks. Submit everything correctly the first time.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">🔍</div>
          <h4>Name checks &amp; security clearance</h4>
          <p>Cases are run through national security databases. Name matches — even if innocent — can hold a case for weeks or months while additional review is completed.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">🏛️</div>
          <h4>Embassy backlogs</h4>
          <p>High-volume embassies like Ciudad Juárez (Mexico), Manila (Philippines), and Guangzhou (China) have consistently long interview queues. Staffing and local conditions can make this worse.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">🌐</div>
          <h4>Country quotas (visa backlogs)</h4>
          <p>Immediate Relatives of U.S. citizens (IR-1/CR-1) are not subject to annual visa number caps, so there is no visa backlog. However, country-specific processing factors and embassy capacity still affect timelines.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="factor-card">
          <div class="factor-icon">📄</div>
          <h4>Incomplete NVC package</h4>
          <p>Submitting documents piecemeal, using wrong translations, or missing a required civil document (police cert, military records, prior divorce decree) triggers checklists and delays case completion by months.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How long does the CR-1 visa take in 2026?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The total CR-1 process takes approximately 18–24 months from filing to visa in hand: 12–18 months for USCIS to approve I-130, 3–6 months for NVC processing (fees + documents + review), and 1–3 months for embassy interview and visa issuance. Unlike the K-1, your spouse arrives already holding permanent resident status — no separate Adjustment of Status process is needed.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How long does USCIS take to process the I-130 for a CR-1 in 2026?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">USCIS is processing Form I-130 for spouses of U.S. citizens (Immediate Relatives) in approximately 12–18 months as of April 2026. Times vary by service center — the National Benefits Center tends to run faster (10–14 months) while the California Service Center tends to run slower (14–18 months). Always verify at egov.uscis.gov/processing-times.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How long does NVC processing take for a CR-1?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">NVC processing for a CR-1 typically takes 3–6 months total: 1–6 weeks to receive a case number and pay fees, 2–6 weeks to compile and upload all documents, 4–12 weeks for NVC review (longer if a checklist is issued), and 2–6 weeks for the embassy to schedule the interview after NVC marks the case complete. Submitting a complete, error-free package is the best way to minimize NVC processing time.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Which countries have the fastest CR-1 interview scheduling?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Lower-volume embassies with efficient operations typically schedule interviews fastest. Canada, Australia, Germany, South Korea, and the United Kingdom often schedule within 1–2 months of NVC completion. High-volume posts — Mexico (Ciudad Juárez), Philippines (Manila), India, and China (Guangzhou) — typically have interview wait times of 3–5 months. Check current wait times at travel.state.gov.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What causes the most CR-1 visa delays?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The most common causes of significant CR-1 delays are: (1) an RFE from USCIS requiring additional marriage evidence — adds 3–6 months; (2) an NVC checklist from an incomplete or incorrect document submission — adds 4–12 weeks; (3) name-check or security clearance holds at USCIS; and (4) embassy interview backlogs at high-volume posts. A well-prepared initial filing and complete NVC package are the best protections against avoidable delays.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How can I speed up my CR-1 visa processing?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">There is no premium processing or expedite option for I-130. The best approach is: file a thorough, well-documented I-130 from the start; respond to any USCIS RFE completely and promptly; compile all NVC documents before submitting (to avoid a checklist); and monitor your case at my.uscis.gov and ceac.state.gov. If your case has exceeded the published USCIS processing time, submit a service request at my.uscis.gov or contact your Congressional representative's office for a formal inquiry.</div>
      </div>
    </section>

